issue(id="0013" status="closed")
  title Enable direct mobile access to scrubs guests via Tailscale SSH
  user-story
    as-a scrubs user programming remotely from my phone
    i-want scrubs guests to be directly reachable over Tailscale with a phone-friendly SSH path
    so-that I can connect to a guest itself rather than depending on host-local Lima forwarding or a desktop intermediary
  premise.
    This now ships as a scrubs base capability when a Tailscale OAuth client
    secret is configured for the selected clean auth profile. Bootstrap seals
    that secret into clean guest auth, materializes it only long enough for
    the guest's NixOS-managed `tailscaled-autoconnect` path to enroll, and
    enables Tailscale SSH without enabling a real guest password.

    The guest keeps its existing Lima-local SSH path for host workflows while
    also joining the tailnet as a tagged node whose hostname is derived from
    the instance name. The chosen model is explicit: Tailscale support lives
    in clean Nix guest configuration, not in dirty `mise` space, and it keeps
    the clean/dirty boundary intact.

    Validation completed on June 3-4, 2026. A real `wayforge` guest enrolled
    successfully, was reachable directly from a phone over Tailscale SSH, and
    kept existing local scrubs flows intact. Along the way, the implementation
    also fixed a Lima boot-order race by making `tailscaled-autoconnect` wait
    for network and resolver readiness and restart on failure.
  acceptance-criteria
    criterion Scrubs has a documented, supported path to make a guest directly reachable from a phone over a tailnet rather than only through host-local `127.0.0.1` Lima forwarding.
    criterion The preferred remote auth path is Tailscale SSH, and the design does not require enabling real guest password authentication as the normal mobile-access path.
    criterion Guest-side Tailscale installation, state, and launch behavior live in clean guest configuration rather than the dirty `mise` runtime or other ambient dirty-space tooling.
    criterion At least one representative guest such as `wayforge` can be enrolled and reached directly from a phone-oriented workflow, with a concrete validation path for both direct SSH use and the intended Codex/ChatGPT mobile SSH-host flow if that client supports it.
    criterion Existing local scrubs workflows remain intact, including bootstrap, `limactl shell <instance>`, host-local SSH access, and the current clean-auth model for `gh` and Codex.
    criterion The resulting documentation explains the operator flow end to end: how a guest joins the tailnet, how its remote identity is discovered or named, how mobile access is initiated, and which client constraints still require compatibility checks.
    criterion The work explicitly documents the threat-model tradeoff of giving a guest first-class network identity and states what remains intentionally disallowed or unchanged.
  review-items
    item(status="covered").
      Tailscale support now lives in scrubs base as a clean-side guest
      capability that activates when the selected clean auth profile provides a
      Tailscale OAuth client secret. Project shims do not need to own the
      feature.
    item(status="covered").
      Enrollment now happens during bootstrap through a host-provided
      Tailscale OAuth client secret with `auth_keys` scope, tagged guest
      registration, `preauthorized=true` by default, and `ephemeral=false` by
      default.
    item(status="covered").
      The phone-oriented path was validated on a real guest. Tailscale SSH
      worked directly from the phone, and the documentation now captures the
      client-compatibility `username+password` fallback for clients that insist
      on password-style auth prompts.
    item(status="covered").
      Guest hostnames remain instance-derived for now. A guest bootstrapped as
      `wayforge` registers a tailnet hostname derived from `wayforge`, which
      is now documented as the supported naming convention.
